Diagnostics¶

Correlation: Pearson’s Correlation Coefficient¶

Tests whether two samples have a linear relationship

Assumptions:

  • Observations in each sample are independent and identically distributed (iid).
  • Observations in each sample are normally distributed.
  • Observations in each sample have the same variance.
  • H0: the two samples are independent.
  • H1: there is a dependency between the samples.

source : https://machinelearningmastery.com/statistical-hypothesis-tests-in-python-cheat-sheet/

In [14]:
from scipy.stats import pearsonr
data1 = lr.conso
data2 = lr.dju
stat, p = pearsonr(data1, data2)
print('stat=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (stat, p))
if p > 0.05:
    print('Probably independent')
else:
    print('Probably dependent')

stat=0.978, p=0.000
Probably dependent

Normality: Shapiro-Wilk Test¶

Tests whether a data sample has a Gaussian distribution

Assumptions: Observations in each sample are independent and identically distributed (iid)

  • H0: the sample has a Gaussian distribution.
  • H1: the sample does not have a Gaussian distribution

https://machinelearningmastery.com/statistical-hypothesis-tests-in-python-cheat-shee

In [16]:
# Shapiro-Wilk Normality Test 
from scipy.stats import shapiro
data = lin_reg.resid
stat, p = shapiro(data)
print('stat=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (stat, p))
if p > 0.05:
    print('Probably Gaussian')
else:
    print('Probably not Gaussian')

stat=0.995, p=0.950
Probably Gaussian

Normalization of the consumption to 18ºC with the dju dataset¶

We have 2 sets of data:

  • A total monthly consumption of electricity over 9 years
  • The delta of ºC to reach a constant temperature of 18ºC over 9 years to balance electric consumption due to heating
  • Total electric consumption = heating consumption + other consumption
  • Normalized electric consumption 18ºC = Total electric consumption - heating consumption = other consumption
  • The linear regression conso vs dju will allow us to estimate the increase of the total consumption for 1 dju
$$ conso = α + 𝛽.dju + ϵ $$$$ consocor = conso - 𝛽.dju = α + ϵ $$

Consumption desaizonalisation – Moving Average (MA)¶

Considering the curve of the normalized electric consumption, we will chose the additive model (constant range around the trend),
rather than the multiplicative model (range proportional to the trend)

  • A time serie has 3 componants: Trend, Seasonality, Residual
  • Aim of desaisonnalization: Absorb seasonality, conserve the trend and minimize residual variance

Seasonality - decomposition¶

In [21]:
# decomposition
conso.index=lr.index.to_timestamp()

plt.show()
  • Observed shows a constant range around the trend => additive model
  • Trend is non-linear (flat, ascending or descending)
  • Seasonal shows a 6 and a 12 months periodicity. We choose s=12 based on a yearly weather cycle
  • Residual seems to be white noise

Stationarity¶

Augmented Dickey-Fuller Unit Root Test¶

Tests whether a time series has a unit root, e.g. has a trend or more generally is autoregressive.

Assumptions : Observations in are temporally ordered

  • H0: a unit root is present (series is non-stationary).
  • H1: a unit root is not present (series is stationary).

Source: https://machinelearningmastery.com/statistical-hypothesis-tests-in-python-cheat-sheet/

In [24]:
# Augmented Dickey-Fuller unit root test
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller

data = conso.conso_cor
stat, p, lags, obs, crit, t = adfuller(data)
print('stat=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (stat, p))
if p > 0.05:
    print('Probably not Stationary')
else:
    print('Probably Stationary')

stat=-1.807, p=0.377
Probably not Stationary

Kwiatkowski-Phillips-Schmidt-Shin¶

Tests whether a time series is trend stationary or not.

Assumptions : Observations in are temporally ordered

  • H0: the time series is not trend-stationary.
  • H1: the time series is trend-stationary.

Source: https://machinelearningmastery.com/statistical-hypothesis-tests-in-python-cheat-sheet/

In [25]:
# Kwiatkowski-Phillips-Schmidt-Shin test
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import kpss
data = conso.conso_cor
stat, p, lags, crit = kpss(data)
print('stat=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (stat, p))
if p > 0.05:
    print('Probably not Stationary')
else:
    print('Probably Stationary')

stat=0.351, p=0.098
Probably not Stationary

Consumption forecast¶

Holt-Winters Method¶

Splitting data¶

In [26]:
# Training model = conso_cor - 12 last months (2018)
df = conso.conso_cor.iloc[:-12]
# Testing model = 12 last months (2018)
df_test = conso.conso_cor.iloc[-12:]

Run and visualize¶

In [27]:
# Triple smoothing alpha, beta, gamma = Holt-Winters
hw = ExponentialSmoothing(df, seasonal_periods=12, trend='add', seasonal='add').fit()
hw_pred = hw.forecast(12)

print(hw.summary())

# performances indexes
y_true_hw = df_test
y_pred_hw = hw_pred

# Root mean square error (RMSE)
rmse = sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true_hw,y_pred_hw))
print("RMSE HOLT-WINTERS:", round(rmse,3))
# Mean absolute percentage error (MAPE)
mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_true_hw - y_pred_hw) / y_true_hw)) * 100
print("MAPE HOLT-WINTERS:  ", round(mape,3))

Forecast: SARIMA method¶

Definitions¶

Configuring a SARIMA requires selecting hyperparameters for both the trend and seasonal elements of the series.

Trend Elements
There are three trend elements that require configuration
They are the same as the ARIMA model

  • p: Trend autoregression order (AR)
  • d: Trend difference order.
  • q: Trend moving average order (MA)

There are four seasonal elements that are not part of ARIMA that must be configured

  • P: Seasonal autoregressive order.
  • D: Seasonal difference order.
  • Q: Seasonal moving average order.
  • m: The number of time steps for a single seasonal period.

Together, the notation for an SARIMA model is specified as:

  • SARIMA(p,d,q)(P,D,Q)m

source : https://machinelearningmastery.com/sarima-for-time-series-forecasting-in-python/

Stationnarity¶

Augmented Dickey-Fuller Unit Root Test
Tests whether a time series has a unit root, e.g. has a trend or more generally is autoregressive.

Assumptions: Observations in are temporally ordered

  • H0: a unit root is present (series is non-stationary).
  • H1: a unit root is not present (series is stationary).
In [33]:

if p > 0.05:
    print('Probably not Stationary')
else:
    print('Probably Stationary')

Probably not Stationary

Kwiatkowski-Phillips-Schmidt-Shin
Tests whether a time series is trend stationary or not.

Assumptions : Observations in are temporally ordered

  • H0: the time series is not trend-stationary.
  • H1: the time series is trend-stationary.

Grid search for SARIMA model¶

In [39]:
# Spliting the data
df = conso.conso_cor.iloc[:-12]
df_test = conso.conso_cor.iloc[-12:]
pred = 12

Identifying the order of differencing:

  • d=0 if the series has no visible trend or ACF at all lags is low.
  • d≥1 if the series has visible trend or positive ACF values out to a high number of lags.

Note: If you find the best d to be d=1 then the original series has a constant trend. A model with d=2 assumes that the original series has a time-varying trend.

Identifying the number of AR and MA terms

  • p is equal to the first lag where the PACF value is above the significance level.
  • q is equal to the first lag where the ACF value is above the significance level.

Identifying the seasonal part of the model:

  • S is equal to the ACF lag with the highest value (typically at a high lag).

  • D=1 if the series has a stable seasonal pattern over time.

  • D=0 if the series has an unstable seasonal pattern over time.

Rules of thumb:

  • d+D≤2
  • P≥1 if the ACF is positive at lag S, else P=0.
  • Q≥1 if the ACF is negative at lag S, else Q=0.

source: https://www.datasciencecentral.com/profiles/blogs/tutorial-forecasting-with-seasonal-arima

Trend element of the model (p,d,q)

  • p = 3 (first lag where the PACF value is above the significance level)
  • q = 3 (first lag where the ACF value is above the significance level)
  • d = 0 (no visible trend = herratic trend)

Seasonal element of the model (P, D, Q)m

  • m = 12 (ACF lag with the highest value, consumptions based on a yearly cycle)
  • P ≥ 1 = 2 (ACF is positive at lag m, 2m lag still significant)
  • Q = 0 (ACF is positive at lag m)
  • D ≥ 1 = 2 (assumes that the series has a time-varying trend)

Auto SARIMA¶

  • pmdarima is a python package that detects the optimal SARIMA model like R's auto.sarima functionality

source: https://alkaline-ml.com/pmdarima/tips_and_tricks.html

In [44]:
# exogenous -> outside factors (e.g other time series)
# m -> seasonal cycle length
# max_order -> maximum amount of variables to be used in the regression (p + q)
# max_p -> maximum AR components
# max_q -> maximum MA components
# max_d -> maximum Integrations
# maxiter -> maximum iterations we're giving the model to converge the coefficients (becomes harder as the order increases)
# alpha -> level of significance, default is 5%, which we should be using most of the time
# n_jobs -> how many models to fit at a time (-1 indicates "as many as possible")
# trend -> "ct" usually
# information_criterion -> 'aic', 'aicc', 'bic', 'hqic', 'oob' 
#        (Akaike Information Criterion, Corrected Akaike Information Criterion,
#        Bayesian Information Criterion, Hannan-Quinn Information Criterion, or
#        "out of bag"--for validation scoring--respectively)
# out_of_sample -> validates the model selection (pass the entire dataset, and set 20% to be the out_of_sample_size)

# performances indexes
y_true_sm = df_test

print("RMSE SARIMA:", round(rmse,3))
# Mean absolute percentage error (MAPE)
mape = np.mean(np.abs((y_true_sm - y_pred_sm) / y_true_sm)) * 100
print("MAPE SARIMA:  ", round(mape,3))
